Day 3 of hashtag#100DaysOfData 🎯
If SQL joins confuse you, this example will fix that.

Two SQL joins. One simple way to remember them.
Imagine your school has 2 lists:
📋 List A — all students
📋 List B — students who submitted homework
INNER JOIN → only students on BOTH lists (submitted homework ✅)
LEFT JOIN → ALL students from List A. Didn't submit? You show up with a blank (NULL)

Now same logic, real world 👇

You have 100 customers.
You check who logged into your app this month.
Only 60 logged in.

INNER JOIN → shows only the 60 who logged in. 
The other 40 don't exist in the result ❌
LEFT JOIN → shows all 100 customers. 60 logged in ✅ 40 show up with NULL 👀
Just like the students who didn't submit —
these 40 customers didn't show up either.

That NULL is a churn risk signal 🚨
"These 40 customers haven't logged in. They might cancel soon. One can flag them for the customer success team."

Rule to remember:
→ INNER JOIN — only rows that match in BOTH tables
→ LEFT JOIN — ALL rows from the left table + NULL where there's no match

In data, missing rows are often the most important ones.
NULLs aren't empty data. They're answers.

